word_summaries_chapter_104:
  104:1:1:"The first word of verse (104:1) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>)."
  104:1:2:"The second word of verse (104:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"for\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf lām lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ل ل</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  104:1:3:"The third word of verse (104:1) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hā mīm zāy</i> (<span class=\"at\">ه م ز</span>)."
  104:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:1) is an indefinite feminine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">lām mīm zāy</i> (<span class=\"at\">ل م ز</span>)."
  104:2:1:"The first word of verse (104:2) is a masculine singular relative pronoun."
  104:2:2:"The second word of verse (104:2) is a perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">jīm mīm ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ج م ع</span>)."
  104:2:3:"The third word of verse (104:2) is an indefinite masculine noun and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm wāw lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">م و ل</span>)."
  104:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:2) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, verb and object pronoun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The form II perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn dāl dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع د د</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine singular."
  104:3:1:"The first word of verse (104:3) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā sīn bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح س ب</span>)."
  104:3:2:"The second word of verse (104:3) is an accusative particle which belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>)."
  104:3:3:"The third word of verse (104:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A noun and possessive pronoun. The noun is masculine and is in the accusative case (<span class=\"at\">منصوب</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm wāw lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">م و ل</span>). The attached possessive pronoun is third person masculine singular."
  104:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā lām dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ل د</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person masculine singular."
  104:4:1:"The first word of verse (104:4) is an aversion particle."
  104:4:2:"The second word of verse (104:4) is divided into 3 morphological segments. An emphatic prefix, verb and emphatic suffix. The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"surely\" or \"indeed\" and is used to add emphasis. The passive imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn bā dhāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ب ذ</span>). The suffixed emphatic particle is known as the <i class=\"ab\">nūn</i> of emphasis (<span class=\"at\">نون التوكيد</span>)."
  104:4:3:"The third word of verse (104:4) is a preposition."
  104:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:4) is a feminine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā ṭā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح ط م</span>)."
  104:5:1:"The first word of verse (104:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and interrogative noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  104:5:2:"The second word of verse (104:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl rā yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ر ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  104:5:3:"The third word of verse (104:5) is an interrogative noun."
  104:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:5) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā ṭā mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح ط م</span>)."
  104:6:1:"The first word of verse (104:6) is a feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn wāw rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن و ر</span>)."
  104:6:2:"The second word of verse (104:6) is a proper noun in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The proper noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza lām hā</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ل ه</span>)."
  104:6:3:"The third word of verse (104:6) is a form IV feminine passive participle and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The passive participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw qāf dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ق د</span>)."
  104:7:1:"The first word of verse (104:7) is a feminine singular relative pronoun."
  104:7:2:"The second word of verse (104:7) is a form VIII imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is third person feminine singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā lām ʿayn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ل ع</span>)."
  104:7:3:"The third word of verse (104:7) is a preposition."
  104:7:4:"The fourth word of verse (104:7) is a masculine plural noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">fā hamza dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ف أ د</span>)."
  104:8:1:"The first word of verse (104:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. An accusative particle and object pronoun. The accusative particle belongs to a special group of words known as <i class=\"ab\">inna</i> and her sisters (<span class=\"at\">ان واخواتها</span>). The attached object pronoun is third person feminine singular."
  104:8:2:"The second word of verse (104:8) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person masculine plural. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  104:8:3:"The third word of verse (104:8) is an indefinite feminine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw ṣād dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ص د</span>)."
  104:9:1:"The first word of verse (104:9) is a preposition."
  104:9:2:"The second word of verse (104:9) is an indefinite masculine plural noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn mīm dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع م د</span>)."
  104:9:3:"The third word of verse (104:9) is an indefinite form II feminine passive participle and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The passive participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">mīm dāl dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">م د د</span>)."